  "A function whose derivative equals f(x)": "",
  "The reciprocal of f'(x)": "",
  "A function that is always increasing": "",
  "The negative of the derivative of f(x)": "",
  "An antiderivative (or indefinite integral) of f(x) is a function F(x) such that F'(x) = f(x). For example, x^3/3 is an antiderivative of x^2.": "",
  "What does the 'Fundamental Theorem of Calculus' (Part 1) state?": "",
  "Every function has a derivative": "",
  "Riemann sums always overestimate the true area": "",
  "If F is an antiderivative of f, then the integral from a to b of f(x) dx equals F(b) - F(a)": "",
  "The area under any curve equals the derivative at its midpoint": "",
  "The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus connects differentiation and integration: if F'(x) = f(x), then the definite integral from a to b of f(x) dx equals F(b) - F(a).": "",
  "What is the 'trapezoidal rule'?": "",
  "A rule for finding the area of a trapezoid shape": "",
  "A method that uses trapezoids instead of rectangles to approximate area under a curve": "",
  "A technique for solving differential equations": "",
  "A method to find critical points of a function": "",
  "The trapezoidal rule approximates the area under a curve by connecting consecutive points with straight lines, forming trapezoids. It typically gives a better estimate than left or right Riemann sums.": "",
  "What does 'upper sum' mean in Riemann sum terminology?": "",
  "A Riemann sum using the maximum function value in each subinterval": "",
  "The integral of the upper half of a function": "",
  "The sum of all positive function values": "",
  "A Riemann sum using only the right endpoints": "",
  "An upper sum (or upper Riemann sum) uses the supremum (maximum) of f(x) on each subinterval as the rectangle height. This always overestimates the area for a positive function.": "",
  "What does 'midpoint rule' refer to?": "",
  "Using the function value at the midpoint of each subinterval for the rectangle height": "",
  "Finding the median value of the function": "",
  "Averaging the left and right Riemann sums": "",
  "Splitting the interval at its center point only": "",
  "The midpoint rule evaluates f at the midpoint of each subinterval to determine the rectangle height. It often provides a more accurate estimate than left or right endpoint rules.": "",
